procMems.c now stores the mem regions in an array.

This is for interacting with go: we just call this function to get all the
memory regions, and maybe then find a specific string.

The memory regions may change so we may have to take a different approach
in the future.
pid is now a parameter
Add some documentation to procMems.c
Fix indentation.

Memory Regions Listings for windows.

This is something similar to /proc/<pid>/maps in linux, but with less info
and more pain.
memory grep for linux
added linux folder

Change project name to MASCHE

We are now MASCHE! :)
It stands for Memory Analysis Suite for Controlling Harmony of Endpoints.

Fix build errors in linux

I didn't see that after changing the pids to uint
the linux program wouldn't build.
Set C indentation to 4 spaces instead of tab.

Avoid double free of res->modules

I forgot to set the modules to NULL before cleanup. If there was an error
with the GetModuleFilenameEx or GetModuleInformation API Call, it would
make a double free.

It should point to the github repo, not the local package.

To compile it: make regions
To use it:     sudo ./regions <pid>

This program just lists all the pids in the system for windows, using

This program greps the /proc/<pid>/maps for each processes and checks
which processes has a library that matches the regexp.

Fix race condition on TestSearchInOtherProcess

There was a race condition between when we spawn the process and when the process started running: if we searched the memory before the child process initialized its own memory, we may fail our test.

The quick and dirty solution was to synchronize the processes via stdout: From the go test we wait until the process writes something to its StdoutPipe, and from the C process we call printf and fflush after initializing all the memory.

FindProcWithLib now returns the list of softerrors

There was another approach to solving this issue:
Returning only one error which the caller should check if it is a
harderror or a softerror (something similar to PathError in OS Package),
but the problem with that is that softerrors are not errors per se: The
function may have succeded for a lot of processes and failed only for a
few ones, thus, the returning value is still useful. The logic for
handling that case would be a bit complicated (instead of: If it is not a
hard error, then I have useful results).

This resolves #8.

[memaccess/linux] Fix NextReadableMemoryRegion

A detailed explanation of what was fixed and changed, in chronological
order:

    - Several errors where raised in the test because of not ignoring
      unreadable regions. Added as it was a simple test.

    - [vsyscall] mapping was giving errors while trying to read it.
      I googled about it, and it turns out to be a special page always
      mapped by the kernel to optimize some simple syscalls. It can't be
      read so we ignore it.

    - Line splitting was handling errors incorrectly. We only know how to
      parse the current format of the mappings, if it changes this
      program will break, and it'd be better if it breaks in a
      predictable way. In order to do that I changed the split to a
      regexp based one splitting by several space characters, not just
      by one. This way items slice will contain only the non-blank bits
      of the mapping. Finally we check if the length of that slice is
      exactly the one that we were expecting, and if not, we return a
      hard error.

    - The interface says that contiguous regions are collapsed into one,
      and this logic was missing, which could break the algorithms that
      relay on this, so I added it.

    - We were reading unnecessary mappings from the maps file (not a big
      deal) and reporting any soft error that happened during this
      (which can be really confusing while debugging). To avoid this
      the address must be passed to getMappedAdresses, and it's
      intention would be changed to mimic exactly what
      NextReadableMemoryRegion is supposed to do, so I combined them in
      a single function.

    - Finally, mapInfo was representing exactly the same thing as
      MemoryRegion, so I removed the first and used public type
      everywhere.

[memacess/linux] Read the entire process memory

Until we have a good explanation and a different API giving the user the
ability to choose what to read, we read the entire memory of a process.

Also, the previous implementation was hiding several errors in the code, so
it's better if we cover all the cases now, and in the future give add
more granularity about what to read.

value NoRegionAvailable is returned. I changed Linux's
NextReadableMemoryRegion to behave like that.

      intention would be changed to mimic exactly what
      NextReadableMemoryRegion is supposed to do, so I combined them in
      a single function.

    - Finally, mapInfo was representing exactly the same thing as
      MemoryRegion, so I removed the first and used public type
      everywhere.

[memacess/linux] Read the entire process memory

Until we have a good explanation and a different API giving the user the
ability to choose what to read, we read the entire memory of a process.

Also, the previous implementation was hiding several errors in the code, so
it's better if we cover all the cases now, and in the future give add
more granularity about what to read.
